  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT151-kilavi">poruḷ valikkappaṭṭa neñciṟkut talaimakaṉ colliyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Uttered by HIM to his heart that was keen on wealth.</p>
      </div>


      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT151">
          <l> vaṅkāk kaṭanta ceṅkāṟ pēṭai</l>
          <l> yeḻāluṟa vīḻnteṉak kaṇavaṟ kāṇātu</l>
          <l> kuḻalicaik kurala kuṟumpala vakavuṅ</l>
          <l> kuṉṟukeḻu ciṟuneṟi yariya veṉṉātu</l>
          <l> maṟapparuṅ kātali yoḻiya</l>
          <l> viṟappa leṉpatīṇ ṭiṉmaikku muṭivē.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>Here<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">īṇṭu</term> "here" can be used like Skt. iha
            as a particle of universalisation (cf. Srinivasan 1967: 194 n. 131).</note> [is] the end
            to destitution</l>
          <l rend="indent3">– to say: I traverse,<note place="foot">Unclear is whether <term xml:lang="ta">ciṟu neṟi</term> has to be taken as a direct object to <term xml:lang="ta">iṟappal</term>.
            An elliptical statement is equally possible, which would mean to supplement one of the
            usual direct objects of <term xml:lang="ta">iṟa-ttal</term> like <term xml:lang="ta">
            kāṭu</term> and to understand the <term xml:lang="ta">eṉṉātu</term> sentence as a
            further qualification.</note></l>
          <l rend="indent">while [my] love, who is difficult to forget, stays behind,</l>
          <l rend="indent">without saying they are difficult, the small hilly ways</l>
          <l rend="indent">where the red-legged female left behind by the Vaṅkā bird</l>
          <l rend="indent">is calling many short flute-sound voiced [notes],</l>
          <l rend="indent">without seeing [her] husband,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">because the Eḻāl bird has descended to take her. <note place="foot"> ...
            because <choice>
                <seg>she</seg>
                <seg>he</seg>
              </choice> has fallen so that the Eḻāl bird will take <choice>
                <seg>[her]</seg>
                <seg>[him]<note place="foot">So in this case she would call out in fear for him.</note></seg>
              </choice>
            </note>
          </l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
